    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-22T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-22T18:00:00-05:00" n="578"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d578">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/3393: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gordon</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-22T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 22, 1937—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>29. Your 47, July 17, 1 p.m. In response to a personal telegram from the Under
                    Secretary requesting that Ambassador Bullitt,<note n="85" xml:id="d578fn85"
                        >William C. Bullitt, Ambassador in France.</note> if favorable opportunity
                    should arise, express to Delbos<note n="86" xml:id="d578fn86">Yvon Delbos,
                        French Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> our difficulty in understanding
                    the insistence of the French Government in obtaining an additional settlement on
                    the 1910 Haitian loan as a condition precedent to the granting of a reasonable
                    quota for Haitian coffee, Mr. Bullitt cabled as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I spoke to Delbos in the presence of both Chautemps<note n="87"
                                xml:id="d578fn87">Camille Chautemps, French Minister of
                                State.</note> and Blum<note n="88" xml:id="d578fn88">Leon Blum,
                                French President of the Council of Ministers.</note> with regard to
                            the attitude of the French Government toward Haiti.</p>
                        <p>Delbos said that he knew nothing whatsoever about the matter; that it had
                            never even been mentioned to him. He promised to inform himself
                            immediately and asserted as did Chautemps that the French Government
                            would desire to do everything possible to meet the wishes of our
                            Government in any matter concerning Haiti.</p>
                        <p>I shall discuss the question with Delbos at our next meeting.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
